    orch = PhysicsOrchestrator()
    
    # 1. Upgrade Main Topics (categories.json)
    # These are already in orch.data["topics"]
    rel = orch.data["topics"]["relativity"]
    rel["content"] = "<p>Special Relativity is the physical theory governing the relationship between space and time for observers in uniform motion. Formulated by Albert Einstein in 1905, it replaced the Newtonian concept of absolute space and time with a unified four-dimensional <strong>Minkowski Spacetime</strong> manifold. It anchors our <strong>Physical Causality</strong> in the realization that the <strong>Speed of Light (\\( c \\))</strong> is an absolute cosmic limit, fundamentally altering our <strong>Ontological Commitments</strong> to the nature of simultaneity and mass.</p><h3>1. Postulates and the Invariance of c</h3><p>The theory is derived from two fundamental postulates: the laws of physics are identical in all <strong>Inertial Frames</strong>, and the speed of light in a vacuum is a universal constant for all observers. This implies that time and space are not independent but are linked by <strong>Lorentz Transformations</strong>. In university-level mechanics, this invariance is the basis for the <strong>Geometric Origin</strong> of all relativistic effects, ensuring that the <strong>Structure of Spacetime</strong> is hyperbolic rather than Euclidean.</p><h3>2. Time Dilation and Length Contraction</h3><p>Relativity reveals that moving clocks run slow (<strong>Time Dilation</strong>) and moving objects appear shortened in the direction of motion (<strong>Length Contraction</strong>). These effects are not mechanical distortions but geometric projections of the 4D <strong>World-Lines</strong> onto different reference frames. From the perspective of the <strong>Block Universe</strong>, these phenomena prove that time is a coordinate dimension, where the <strong>Proper Time</strong> along a trajectory is the invariant 'Length' of the path.</p><h3>3. Relativistic Mass-Energy Equivalence</h3><p>The most famous result of the theory is the identity \\( E = mc^2 \\). This reveals that mass is a highly concentrated form of energy, providing the <strong>Geometric Origin</strong> for the massive energy release in nuclear processes. In the <strong>Standard Model</strong>, this equivalence allows for the constant interconversion of particles and energy, anchoring <strong>Scientific Realism</strong> in the realization that the vacuum is a dynamic reservoir of potential matter.</p><h3>4. The 4-Vector Formalism</h3><p>Modern theoretical physics expresses special relativity through <strong>4-Vectors</strong> (Position, Momentum, Current). By using the <strong>Metric Tensor (\\( \\eta_{\\mu\\nu} \\))</strong>, physicists define invariants like the <strong>Minkowski Interval</strong>. This tensor calculus ensures that the <strong>Total Dynamics</strong> of a system are <strong>Manifestly Covariant</strong>, meaning they maintain their form across all relativistic transformations, providing the definitive map for <strong>Theoretical Physics</strong>.</p><h3>5. The Causal Structure of the Vacuum</h3><p>Relativity establishes the <strong>Light-Cone</strong> as the ultimate boundary of <strong>Physical Causality</strong>. Events are categorized as <strong>Timelike</strong>, <strong>Spacelike</strong>, or <strong>Lightlike</strong>. This causal topology prevents information from traveling faster than light, protecting the universe from temporal paradoxes and ensuring that the order of cause and effect is objective for all observers within the 4D manifold.</p><h3>6. Epistemic Limits and the Cosmic Speed Limit</h3><p>The speed of light acts as a fundamental <strong>Epistemic Limit</strong>. It restricts the volume of the universe that any observer can ever know or influence. This <strong>Horizon</strong> defines the <strong>Observability</strong> of the cosmos, leading to the <strong>Past Hypothesis</strong> in cosmology. Theoretical physicists use these limits to test the <strong>Geometric Origin</strong> of information processing in the vacuum, seeking the ultimate resolution of the <strong>Block Universe</strong> structure.</p>"
    rel["formula_ids"] = ["lorentz-transformation-8c31", "mass-energy-equivalence-55ff", "minkowski-interval-f5c7"]
    
    qm = orch.data["topics"]["quantum-physics"]
    qm["content"] = "<p>Quantum Mechanics is the fundamental theory of the subatomic world, describing the behavior of matter and energy at the scale of atoms and elementary particles. It replaces the deterministic trajectories of classical mechanics with a probabilistic <strong>State Vector</strong> in <strong>Hilbert Space</strong>. In university-level philosophy of physics, this theory represents a radical <strong>Epistemic Shift</strong>, challenging our notions of <strong>Physical Causality</strong> and the <strong>Scientific Realism</strong> of unobserved properties.</p><h3>1. The Wave Function and Probability Amplitudes</h3><p>The central object of quantum theory is the <strong>Wave Function (\\( \\psi \\))</strong>, which encodes all knowable information about a system. According to the <strong>Born Rule</strong>, the square of the amplitude (\\( |\\psi|^2 \\)) gives the <strong>Probability Density</strong> of finding a particle. This reveals that the 4D manifold is fundamentally stochastic at small scales, where the <strong>Total Dynamics</strong> emerge from the interference of complex phases rather than rigid force vectors.</p><h3>2. Operators and Observables</h3><p>In the quantum framework, physical quantities like energy and momentum are represented by <strong>Linear Operators</strong>. The process of measurement corresponds to the <strong>Eigenvalue Problem</strong>, where the system collapses into a specific state. This <strong>Epistemic Collapse</strong> is the heart of the <strong>Measurement Problem</strong>, forcing physicists to choose between <strong>Many-Worlds</strong>, <strong>Copenhagen</strong>, or <strong>Pilot Wave</strong> interpretations of the <strong>Structure of Spacetime</strong>.</p><h3>3. The Uncertainty Principle</h3><p>Heisenberg's <strong>Uncertainty Principle</strong> asserts a fundamental limit to the precision with which certain pairs of variables (like position and momentum) can be known. This is not a failure of detectors but a property of <strong>Non-Commutative Algebra</strong>. This <strong>Epistemic Limit</strong> ensures that the subatomic vacuum is always 'active' with <strong>Quantum Fluctuations</strong>, providing the <strong>Geometric Origin</strong> for <strong>Hawking Radiation</strong> and the stability of matter.</p><h3>4. Entanglement and Non-Locality</h3><p>When two particles interact, they can become <strong>Entangled</strong>, sharing a single holistic state across any distance. This <strong>Quantum Non-Locality</strong> was famously challenged by the <strong>EPR Paradox</strong> but later confirmed by <strong>Bell Tests</strong>. It suggests that the universe is <strong>Non-Separable</strong>, where the <strong>Physical Link</strong> between entities is more fundamental than their spatial separation, a key pillar of <strong>Structural Realism</strong>.</p><h3>5. Unitary Evolution: The TDSE</h3><p>The time-evolution of a quantum system is governed by the <strong>Schrödinger Equation</strong>, which ensures that total probability is conserved through <strong>Unitary Transformation</strong>. This determinism of the wave function (Process 2) contrasts with the randomness of measurement (Process 1), anchoring <strong>Physical Causality</strong> in the evolution of the <strong>Hamiltonian Operator</strong> rather than the motion of individual particles.</p><h3>6. The Path Integral and Sum Over Histories</h3><p>Richard Feynman's <strong>Path Integral Formulation</strong> provides a bridge between classical and quantum regimes. It asserts that a system traverses <em>every possible history</em> simultaneously, with the classical path emerging as the one of <strong>Stationary Action</strong>. This <strong>Geometric Optimization</strong> reveals that <strong>Classical Mechanics</strong> is an emergent limit of the <strong>Total Dynamics</strong> of the quantum vacuum, providing the ultimate map for <strong>Mathematical Realism</strong>.</p>"
    qm["formula_ids"] = ["schrodinger-equation-c9885ce7", "uncertainty-relation-8c31", "born-rule-f5c7"]

    # 2. Add New Subtopic (The Big Bang)
    big_bang = {
        "title": "The Big Bang",
        "parents": ["astrophysics"],
        "content": "<p>The Big Bang is the prevailing cosmological model for the <strong>Geometric Origin</strong> and evolution of the universe. It asserts that the 4D spacetime manifold originated from a state of extremely high density and temperature approximately 13.8 billion years ago. In university-level cosmology, the Big Bang is not an explosion <em>in</em> space, but the expansion <em>of</em> space itself, governed by the <strong>General Relativity</strong> and the unique <strong>Initial Conditions</strong> of the <strong>Early Universe</strong>.</p><h3>1. The Expansion of the Manifold</h3><p>The primary evidence for the Big Bang is the <strong>Cosmic Expansion</strong> observed through the redshift of distant galaxies. According to <strong>Hubble's Law</strong>, the distance between any two points in the universe is increasing over time. This expansion is modeled by the <strong>Scale Factor (\\( a(t) \\))</strong> in the <strong>Friedmann-Lemaître-Robertson-Walker (FLRW)</strong> metric, showing that the <strong>Structure of Spacetime</strong> is a dynamic participant in the <strong>Total Dynamics</strong> of the cosmos.</p><h3>2. The Cosmic Microwave Background (CMB)</h3><p>The 'Afterglow' of the Big Bang is the <strong>CMB</strong> radiation, which was released during the <strong>Recombination</strong> era when the universe first became transparent. This background radiation is a nearly perfect blackbody, carrying a 4D snapshot of the <strong>Density Fluctuations</strong> that would later form galaxies. The uniformity of the CMB is a primary driver of the <strong>Inflationary Theory</strong>, suggesting a period of super-exponential growth in the first fraction of a second.</p><h3>3. Big Bang Nucleosynthesis (BBN)</h3><p>In the first few minutes, the universe was a dense nuclear reactor. <strong>BBN</strong> correctly predicts the primordial abundances of light elements (Hydrogen, Helium, Lithium), matching observations to extreme precision. This success anchors our <strong>Scientific Realism</strong> in the belief that the subatomic laws of the <strong>Standard Model</strong> were active even at the birth of the 4D <strong>Block Universe</strong>.</p><h3>4. The Problem of the Singularity</h3><p>Classical <strong>General Relativity</strong> predicts that the Big Bang started with a <strong>Physical Singularity</strong> where curvature and density become infinite. Theoretical physicists view this as an <strong>Epistemic Limit</strong>, indicating that our current models are incomplete. The quest for <strong>Quantum Gravity</strong> aims to replace the singularity with a <strong>Big Bounce</strong> or a discrete transition, seeking the fundamental <strong>Geometric Origin</strong> of existence.</p><h3>5. The Past Hypothesis and Entropy</h3><p>The Big Bang represents the <strong>Initial Condition</strong> of <strong>Extremely Low Entropy</strong>. This <strong>Past Hypothesis</strong> is the ultimate source of the <strong>Arrow of Time</strong>. Without this highly ordered beginning, the universe would be in thermal equilibrium, and the complex <strong>History of the Universe</strong> would be physically impossible. This links <strong>Thermodynamics</strong> directly to the <strong>Causal Topology</strong> of the initial state.</p><h3>6. Fine-Tuning and the Multiverse</h3><p>The specific values of the <strong>Constants of Nature</strong> at the Big Bang appear to be <strong>Fine-Tuned</strong> for the emergence of complexity. This leads to the debate over the <strong>Anthropic Principle</strong> and the <strong>Multiverse</strong>. Philosophers and physicists utilize the <strong>Geometric Origin</strong> of these parameters to test whether our Big Bang is a unique necessary event or one of many 'Bubbles' in a vast 11D <strong>M-Theory</strong> landscape.</p>",
        "formula_ids": ["hubble-law-8c31", "flrw-metric-55ff", "entropy-bound-f5c7"]
    }
    orch.add_subtopic("big-bang-theory", big_bang)

